This gives us the relationships: - \( m + n = k \) - \( mn = 36 \) We need to find all pairs of integers \( (m, n) \) such that their product is 36 and they are distinct. We also consider both positive and negative pairs since the roots can be positive or negative integers. First, we list all pairs of positive integers whose product is 36: 1. \( (1, 36) \) 2. \( (2, 18) \) 3. \( (3, 12) \) 4. \( (4, 9) \) Next, we list all pairs of negative integers whose product is 36: 1. \( (-1, -36) \) 2. \( (-2, -18) \) 3. \( (-3, -12) \) 4. \( (-4, -9) \) For each pair, we calculate the sum \( m + n \): - Positive pairs: - \( 1 + 36 = 37 \) - \( 2 + 18 = 20 \) - \( 3 + 12 = 15 \) - \( 4 + 9 = 13 \) - Negative pairs: - \( -1 + (-36) = -37 \) - \( -2 + (-18) = -20 \) - \( -3 + (-12) = -15 \) - \( -4 + (-9) = -13 \) The sums we obtain are \( 37, 20, 15, 13, -37, -20, -15, -13 \). All these sums are distinct, leading to 8 distinct values of \( k \). Thus, the number of values of \( k \) for which the polynomial \( x^2 + kx + 36 \) has two distinct integer roots is \(\boxed{8}\).
